uently through hostile stereotypes, distortions, and caricature. In this provocative book, Erich Gruen demonstrates how the ancients found connections rather than contrasts, how they expressed admiration for the achievements and principles of other societies, and how they discerned--and even invented--kinship relations and shared roots with diverse peoples. Gruen shows how the ancients incorporated the traditions of foreign nations, and imagined blood ties and associations with distant cultures through myth, legend, and fictive histories. He looks at a host of creative tales, including those describing the founding of Thebes by the Phoenician Cadmus, Rome's embrace of Trojan and Arcadian origins, and Abraham as ancestor to the Spartans. Gruen gives in-depth readings of major texts by Aeschylus, Herodotus, Xenophon, Plutarch, Julius Caesar, Tacitus, and others, in addition to portions of the Hebrew Bible, revealing how they offer richly nuanced portraits of the alien that go well beyond stereotypes and caricature. Providing extraordinary insight into the ancient world, this controversial book explores how ancient attitudes toward the Other often expressed mutuality and connection, and not simply contrast and alienation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAliensvPublic opinion. 0aAlienszGreecevPublic opinionxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aAlienszGreecexPublic opinionxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aAlienszRomevPublic opinionxHistory. 0aAlienszRomexPublic opinionxHistory. 0aCivilizationxHistory. 0aCulture conflictxHistory. 0aGreecevCivilizationvTo 146 B.CvForeign influences. 0aGreeksvAttitudesxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aGreeksxAttitudesxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHISTORYvSocial History. 0aRomansvAttitudesxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aRomansxAttitudesxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRomevCivilizationvForeign influences. 0aSOCIA